d international courts, or smaller NGOs that employ satellite imagery, big data analysis, and forensic computing. As the growing number of NGOs vie for limited funding and media attention, smaller, more marginal, groups often adopt radical strategies like enforcement.Looking at the workings of major organizations, including Amnesty International, Greenpeace, and Transparency International, as well as smaller players, such as Global Witness, the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society, and Bellingcat, Vigilantes beyond Borders explores the consequences of a novel, provocative approach to global governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aInternational law. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxPolitical activity. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  aAbortion law.  aAbstention.  aActivism.  aAdvocacy.  aAmerican Declaration of the Rights and Duties of Man.  aAngola.  aBillionaire.  aBlockchain.  aBounty hunter.  aBribery.  aBruno Manser.  aBurkina Faso.  aBy-law.  aCITES.  aChauvinism.  aChild pornography.  aCivil society.  aClientEarth.  aCoat (clothing).  aCoercion.  aCommon area.  aCompetition law.  aCorporation.  aCorruption.  aCostume.  aCourt of public opinion.  aCourt show.  aCrime.  aCriminal justice.  aDavid Hockney.  aDesign technology.  aDirect action.  aDisincentive.  aDrought.  aEmpowerment.  aEnvironmental law.  aEnvironmental politics.  aEuropol.  aFederal government of the United States.  aFinancial innovation.  aFreeman (Colonial).  aGlobal governance.  aGreenpeace.  aGroup call.  aHeadline.  aHigh politics.  aHonorarium.  aHuman Rights Watch.  aHuman rights group.  aIllustration.  aImmigration to the United States.  aIncumbent (ecclesiastical).  aInsider.  aInternationa